    name: 'DO / DOES',
    forms: 'do · does · did',
    description: 'Manages ALL common verbs — any verb that is not BE or HAVE used as auxiliary.',
    rows: [
      { aff: 'She WORKS here. (DO invisible)', neg: "She DOESN'T work here.", q: 'DOES she work here?', nq: "DOESN'T she work here?" },
      { aff: 'They PLAYED well. (DID invisible)', neg: "They DIDN'T play well.", q: 'DID they play well?', nq: "DIDN'T they play well?" },
    ],
    examples: [
      { en: 'My friend works here.', es: 'Mi amigo trabaja aquí.', fr: 'Mon ami travaille ici.', de: 'Mein Freund arbeitet hier.', pt: 'Meu amigo trabalha aqui.' },
      { en: "Do you study English?", es: '¿Estudias inglés?', fr: 'Tu étudies l’anglais ?', de: 'Lernst du Englisch?', pt: 'Você estuda inglês?' },
      { en: "She doesn't know.", es: 'Ella no sabe.', fr: 'Elle ne sait pas.', de: 'Sie weiß es nicht.', pt: 'Ela não sabe.' },
    ],
    note: "Esta regla maneja TODOS los verbos comunes (correr, comer, estudiar, trabajar...). Es INVISIBLE en la afirmación — el verbo aparece solo. Solo aparece en negación y pregunta. DO = I/You/We/They · DOES = He/She/It · DID = todos en pasado.",
    abbrev: "DO NOT = DON'T · DOES NOT = DOESN'T · DID NOT = DIDN'T",
  },
  {
    name: 'HAVE / HAS',
    forms: 'have · has · had',
    description: 'Two meanings: TENER (common verb — managed by DO) and HABER (perfect tense — managed by HAVE itself).',
    rows: [
      { aff: 'I HAVE SLEPT. (perfect)', neg: "I HAVEN'T slept.", q: 'HAVE I slept?', nq: "HAVEN'T I slept?" },
      { aff: 'She HAS EATEN. (perfect)', neg: "She HASN'T eaten.", q: 'HAS she eaten?', nq: "HASN'T she eaten?" },
    ],
    examples: [
      { en: 'I have lived here for 3 years.', es: 'He vivido aquí 3 años.', fr: 'J’habite ici depuis 3 ans.', de: 'Ich lebe seit 3 Jahren hier.', pt: 'Eu moro aqui há 3 anos.' },
      { en: 'She has to work. → Does she have to work?', es: 'Ella tiene que trabajar. → ¿Tiene que trabajar?', fr: 'Elle doit travailler. → Est-ce qu’elle doit travailler ?', de: 'Sie muss arbeiten. → Muss sie arbeiten?', pt: 'Ela tem que trabalhar. → Ela tem que trabalhar?' },
      { en: 'She had studied. vs. She has studied.', es: 'Ella había estudiado. vs. Ella ha estudiado.', fr: 'Elle avait étudié. vs. Elle a étudié.', de: 'Sie hatte gelernt. vs. Sie hat gelernt.', pt: 'Ela tinha estudado. vs. Ela estudou / tem estudado.' },
    ],
    note: "Tiene dos significados: TENER y HABER. Cuando es TENER, es verbo común → lo maneja DO/DOES (Do you have money? / She doesn't have to go). Cuando es HABER, lo maneja HAVE/HAS (Have you eaten? / She hasn't called). HAD = pasado de ambos: 'tenía/tuvo' (maneja DID) y 'había' (maneja HAD).",
    abbrev: "HAVE NOT = HAVEN'T · HAS NOT = HASN'T · HAD NOT = HADN'T",
  },
  {
    name: 'WILL',
    forms: "will · won't",
    description: 'Certain future — strong intention, promise, absolute certainty.',
    rows: [
      { aff: 'I WILL call you.', neg: "I WON'T call you.", q: 'WILL you call?', nq: "WON'T you call?" },
    ],
    examples: [
      { en: 'I will call you later.', es: 'De hecho que te llamo más tarde.', fr: 'Je t’appellerai plus tard.', de: 'Ich rufe dich später an.', pt: 'Eu vou te ligar mais tarde.' },
      { en: "He won't come today.", es: 'Fijo que no viene hoy.', fr: 'Il ne viendra pas aujourd’hui.', de: 'Er wird heute nicht kommen.', pt: 'Ele não vai vir hoje.' },
      { en: "Won't you help me?", es: '¿En serio no me vas a ayudar?', fr: 'Tu ne vas vraiment pas m’aider ?', de: 'Willst du mir wirklich nicht helfen?', pt: 'Você não vai me ajudar mesmo?' },
    ],
    note: "No lo traduzcas solo como '-ré' (trabajaré, iré). Úsalo cuando eres 100% seguro: 'fijo que', 'de hecho que', 'en serio que', 'de todas formas que'. Es dar tu palabra. Si no estás completamente seguro, usa GOING TO o MIGHT.",
    abbrev: "WILL NOT = WON'T",
  },
  {
    name: 'GOING TO',
    forms: 'is/am/are going to · was/were going to',
    description: 'Pre-decided plans (no emphasis). WAS/WERE GOING TO = frustrated plan — something that was planned but did not happen.',
    rows: [
      { aff: 'She IS GOING TO work.', neg: "She ISN'T going to work.", q: 'IS she going to work?', nq: "ISN'T she going to work?" },
      { aff: 'He WAS GOING TO call. (frustrated)', neg: "He WASN'T going to call.", q: 'WAS he going to call?', nq: "WASN'T he going to call?" },
    ],
    examples: [
      { en: 'We are going to move next month.', es: 'Nos vamos a mudar el próximo mes.', fr: 'Nous allons déménager le mois prochain.', de: 'Wir werden nächsten Monat umziehen.', pt: 'Nós vamos nos mudar no próximo mês.' },
      { en: 'She was going to call you.', es: 'Ella te iba a llamar. (pero no lo hizo)', fr: 'Elle allait t’appeler. (mais elle ne l’a pas fait)', de: 'Sie wollte dich anrufen. (aber sie hat es nicht getan)', pt: 'Ela ia te ligar. (mas não ligou)' },
      { en: 'Is he going to travel?', es: '¿Él va a viajar?', fr: 'Est-ce qu’il va voyager ?', de: 'Wird er reisen?', pt: 'Ele vai viajar?' },
    ],
    note: "Solo menciona el futuro sin énfasis — es simplemente el plan ya organizado. IMPORTANTE: GOING TO siempre necesita el verbo BE: IS/AM/ARE going to (presente) · WAS/WERE going to (pasado). Nunca digas 'She GOING TO work' — falta el BE. WAS/WERE GOING TO = futuro frustrado: lo que iba a pasar pero no pasó.",
    abbrev: 'Questions and negatives are always built with BE (is/are/was/were)',
  },
  {
    name: 'WOULD',
    forms: "would · wouldn't",
    description: 'Conditional — what would happen (with an implied or explicit "if").',
    rows: [
      { aff: 'She WOULD listen.', neg: "She WOULDN'T listen.", q: 'WOULD she listen?', nq: "WOULDN'T she listen?" },
    ],
    examples: [
      { en: 'She would listen to you (if you explained).', es: 'Ella te escucharía (si le explicaras).', fr: 'Elle t’écouterait (si tu expliquais).', de: 'Sie würde dir zuhören (wenn du es erklären würdest).', pt: 'Ela te escutaria (se você explicasse).' },
      { en: "They wouldn't understand.", es: 'Ellos no entenderían.', fr: 'Ils ne comprendraient pas.', de: 'Sie würden es nicht verstehen.', pt: 'Eles não entenderiam.' },
      { en: 'Would you help me?', es: '¿Me ayudarías?', fr: 'Pourrais-tu m’aider ?', de: 'Würdest du mir helfen?', pt: 'Você me ajudaria?' },
    ],
    note: "Expresa lo que alguien haría en una condición: 'haría, diría, iría, vendría...' Siempre hay una condición implícita o explícita (si..., if...). También se usa para peticiones muy educadas: 'Would you...?' es más formal que 'Can you...?'",
    abbrev: "WOULD NOT = WOULDN'T",
  },
  {
    name: 'SHOULD',
    forms: "should · shouldn't",
    description: 'Strong recommendation or moral obligation — but with free will. There are consequences if ignored, but it is not a command.',
    rows: [
      { aff: 'You SHOULD study.', neg: "You SHOULDN'T skip it.", q: 'SHOULD she study?', nq: "SHOULDN'T she study?" },
    ],
    examples: [
      { en: 'They should come with you.', es: 'Ellos deberían venir contigo.', fr: 'Ils devraient venir avec toi.', de: 'Sie sollten mit dir kommen.', pt: 'Eles deveriam vir com você.' },
      { en: "She shouldn't stop studying.", es: 'Ella no debería dejar de estudiar.', fr: 'Elle ne devrait pas arrêter d’étudier.', de: 'Sie sollte nicht aufhören zu lernen.', pt: 'Ela não deveria parar de estudar.' },
      { en: "Shouldn't he work harder?", es: '¿No debería esforzarse más?', fr: 'Ne devrait-il pas travailler plus dur ?', de: 'Sollte er nicht härter arbeiten?', pt: 'Ele não deveria se esforçar mais?' },
    ],
    note: "'Debería' — no es una orden ni una obligación forzada. Existe libre albedrío: la persona puede no hacerlo. Pero si no lo hace, habrá consecuencias. Es un compromiso moral fuerte, no una imposición. Solo en presente — no tiene forma de pasado directo.",
    abbrev: "SHOULD NOT = SHOULDN'T",
  },
  {
    name: 'COULD',
    forms: "could · couldn't",
    description: 'Past and conditional of CAN — past ability, polite requests, possibility.',
    rows: [
      { aff: 'She COULD help.', neg: "She COULDN'T help.", q: 'COULD she help?', nq: "COULDN'T she help?" },
    ],
    examples: [
      { en: "She couldn't come yesterday.", es: 'Ella no pudo venir ayer.', fr: 'Elle n’a pas pu venir hier.', de: 'Sie konnte gestern nicht kommen.', pt: 'Ela não pôde vir ontem.' },
      { en: 'Could you call me tomorrow?', es: '¿Podrías llamarme mañana?', fr: 'Pourrais-tu m’appeler demain ?', de: 'Könntest du mich morgen anrufen?', pt: 'Você poderia me ligar amanhã?' },
      { en: "I could help you (if you asked).", es: 'Yo podría ayudarte (si me lo pidieras).', fr: 'Je pourrais t’aider (si tu me le demandais).', de: 'Ich könnte dir helfen (wenn du fragen würdest).', pt: 'Eu poderia te ajudar (se você pedisse).' },
    ],
    note: "'Podría, podía, pudo' — es el pasado y condicional de CAN. Úsalo para hablar de habilidad en el pasado ('she couldn't come') o para peticiones educadas ('could you...?'). Es más cortés que CAN para preguntas.",
    abbrev: "COULD NOT = COULDN'T",
  },
  {
    name: 'CAN / BE ABLE TO',
    forms: "can · can't · be able to",
    description: 'CAN = personal decision or willingness to act. BE ABLE TO = physical or situational capacity.',
    rows: [
      { aff: 'I CAN help.', neg: "I CAN'T help.", q: 'CAN you help?', nq: "CAN'T you help?" },
      { aff: 'I AM ABLE TO work.', neg: 'I AM NOT ABLE TO work.', q: 'Are you able to work?', nq: '' },
    ],
    examples: [
      { en: "I can't work like this!", es: '¡No puedo trabajar así! (No quiero / no me da la gana)', fr: 'Je ne peux pas travailler comme ça ! (volonté / refus)', de: 'So kann ich nicht arbeiten! (Wille / Ablehnung)', pt: 'Eu não consigo trabalhar assim! (vontade / recusa)' },
      { en: 'I am not able to work like this.', es: 'No puedo trabajar así. (Estoy físicamente incapacitado)', fr: 'Je ne suis pas capable de travailler comme ça. (capacité réelle)', de: 'Ich bin nicht in der Lage, so zu arbeiten. (echte Fähigkeit)', pt: 'Eu não sou capaz de trabalhar assim. (capacidade real)' },
      { en: 'Are you going to be able to come?', es: '¿Vas a poder venir? (¿Estarás en condiciones?)', fr: 'Est-ce que tu vas pouvoir venir ? (seras-tu en mesure de venir ?)', de: 'Wirst du kommen können? (wirst du dazu in der Lage sein?)', pt: 'Você vai conseguir vir? (vai estar em condições?)' },
    ],
    note: "CAN = 'puedo' porque quiero / decido hacerlo. Expresa poder por decisión personal — incluso cuando en realidad no pueda. BE ABLE TO = 'puedo' porque estoy físicamente apto o habilitado. La situación o el cuerpo me habilita. La diferencia es sutil pero real: CAN es de la voluntad, BE ABLE TO es de la capacidad.",
    abbrev: "CAN NOT = CAN'T",
  },
  {
    name: 'MAY',
    forms: 'may · may not',
    description: '50/50 probability OR formal permission request.',
    rows: [
      { aff: 'They MAY call.', neg: 'They MAY NOT call.', q: 'MAY I come in?', nq: '—' },
    ],
    examples: [
      { en: 'They may call you tomorrow.', es: 'Talvez te llamen mañana. (50/50)', fr: 'Ils t’appelleront peut-être demain. (50/50)', de: 'Vielleicht rufen sie dich morgen an. (50/50)', pt: 'Talvez eles te liguem amanhã. (50/50)' },
      { en: 'We may not come tonight.', es: 'Quizás no vengamos esta noche.', fr: 'Il se peut que nous ne venions pas ce soir.', de: 'Vielleicht kommen wir heute Abend nicht.', pt: 'Talvez não venhamos hoje à noite.' },
      { en: 'May I come in?', es: '¿Me permite entrar? (muy formal)', fr: 'Puis-je entrer ? (très formel)', de: 'Darf ich hereinkommen? (sehr formell)', pt: 'Posso entrar? (muito formal)' },
    ],
    note: "Dos usos: (1) Probabilidad 50/50 — 'talvez, quizás'. No estás seguro ni en contra. (2) Pregunta formal de permiso: MAY I...? es mucho más educado que CAN I...? — úsalo con personas de alta autoridad o cuando necesitas ser muy respetuoso. También: 'May you and your family have a great year' = un deseo formal, escrito.",
    abbrev: 'MAY NOT (no contraction)',
  },
  {
    name: 'MUST',
    forms: "must · must not",
    description: 'Strong obligation — there will be consequences if not done. Also logical deduction.',
    rows: [
      { aff: 'You MUST study.', neg: 'You MUST NOT skip it. (prohibition)', q: '—', nq: '—' },
    ],
    examples: [
      { en: 'You must study for the exam tomorrow.', es: 'Debes estudiar para el examen mañana.', fr: 'Tu dois étudier pour l’examen demain.', de: 'Du musst für die Prüfung morgen lernen.', pt: 'Você deve estudar para a prova amanhã.' },
      { en: 'She must not stop studying.', es: 'Ella no debe dejar de estudiar.', fr: 'Elle ne doit pas arrêter d’étudier.', de: 'Sie darf nicht aufhören zu lernen.', pt: 'Ela não deve parar de estudar.' },
      { en: "He must be tired. (deduction)", es: 'Debe estar cansado. (deducción lógica)', fr: 'Il doit être fatigué. (déduction logique)', de: 'Er muss müde sein. (logische Schlussfolgerung)', pt: 'Ele deve estar cansado. (dedução lógica)' },
    ],
    note: "'Deber imprescindible' — no es una orden de alguien más, es una norma. Si no la cumples, habrá consecuencias. No confundas con SHOULD (recomendación con libre albedrío) ni con HAVE TO (obligación externa que te imponen). MUST solo existe en presente. Para el pasado: usa HAD TO.",
    abbrev: 'MUST NOT = MUSTN\'T (prohibition, stronger than SHOULD NOT)',
  },
];

const getExampleTranslation = (example: Record<string, string>) =>
  currentLocale === 'en' ? '' : example[currentLocale] ?? '';

const mistakeNoteKeys = {
  es: 'noteEs',
  fr: 'noteFr',
  de: 'noteDe',
  pt: 'notePt',
} as const;

const getMistakeNote = (item: Record<string, string>) =>
  currentLocale === 'en' ? item.note : item[mistakeNoteKeys[currentLocale]] ?? item.note;
---

<h1 class="font-headline text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold tracking-display text-on-surface mb-3">
  {copy.title}
</h1>
<p class="text-on-surface-variant text-lg leading-relaxed mb-10 max-w-2xl">
  {copy.introBefore}<strong class="text-on-surface font-semibold">{copy.introStrong}</strong>{copy.introAfter}
</p>

{currentLocale !== 'en' && (
  <div class="mb-10 p-4 rounded-2xl bg-primary/8 border border-primary/20 text-sm text-on-surface-variant">
    <span class="text-primary font-semibold">{copy.speakerNoteTitle}</span> {copy.speakerNote}
  </div>
)}

<!-- Auxiliary verb rules -->
<section class="mb-12">
  <h2 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-6 flex items-center gap-2">
    <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-primary" style="font-size:22px">rule</span>
    {copy.rulesTitle}
  </h2>

  <div class="space-y-5">
    {rules.map((rule) => (
      <div class="rounded-2xl bg-surface-container border border-outline-variant/15 overflow-hidden">
        <!-- Rule header -->
        <div class="px-5 pt-5 pb-3 flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="text-primary font-bold font-headline text-base bg-primary/10 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg shrink-0 leading-snug">
            {rule.name}
          </span>
          <div class="pt-1 min-w-0">
            <p class="text-on-surface text-sm font-medium leading-snug">{getRuleDescription(rule)}</p>
            <p class="text-on-surface-variant/60 text-xs mt-0.5">{rule.forms}</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- BE conjugation breakdown -->
        {rule.name === 'BE' && (
          <div class="px-5 pb-3">
            <div class="flex gap-2 text-xs">
              <div class="flex-1 p-2.5 rounded-lg bg-surface-container-high border border-outline-variant/10">
                <span class="text-on-surface-variant/60 font-medium block mb-1">{copy.conjugationLabels.present}</span>
                <span class="text-on-surface font-mono">{beConjugation.present}</span>
                {copy.beEquivalent.present && (
                  <span class="block text-primary/70 mt-1">{copy.beEquivalent.present}</span>
                )}
              </div>
              <div class="flex-1 p-2.5 rounded-lg bg-surface-container-high border border-outline-variant/10">
                <span class="text-on-surface-variant/60 font-medium block mb-1">{copy.conjugationLabels.past}</span>
                <span class="text-on-surface font-mono">{beConjugation.past}</span>
                {copy.beEquivalent.past && (
                  <span class="block text-primary/70 mt-1">{copy.beEquivalent.past}</span>
                )}
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        )}

        <!-- Quick reference table -->
        <div class="px-5 pb-3 overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full text-xs text-left border-collapse min-w-[520px]">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-outline-variant/20">
                <th class="py-1.5 pr-4 text-on-surface-variant/60 font-medium">{copy.headers[0]}</th>
                <th class="py-1.5 pr-4 text-on-surface-variant/60 font-medium">{copy.headers[1]}</th>
                <th class="py-1.5 pr-4 text-on-surface-variant/60 font-medium">{copy.headers[2]}</th>
                <th class="py-1.5 text-on-surface-variant/60 font-medium">{copy.headers[3]}</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-on-surface-variant">
              {rule.rows.map((row) => (
                <tr class="border-b border-outline-variant/10 last:border-none">
                  <td class="py-2 pr-4">
                    {'tenseKey' in row && row.tenseKey && (
                      <span class="block text-[10px] text-primary/60 font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider mb-0.5">
                        {copy.conjugationLabels[row.tenseKey]}
                      </span>
                    )}
                    {row.aff}
                  </td>
                  <td class="py-2 pr-4">{row.neg}</td>
                  <td class="py-2 pr-4">{row.q}</td>
                  <td class="py-2">{row.nq}</td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <!-- Examples -->
        <div class="px-5 pb-3 space-y-1.5">
          {rule.examples.map((ex) => (
            <div class="flex gap-2 text-sm">
              <span class="text-primary shrink-0">→</span>
              <span class="text-on-surface-variant">
                <span class="text-on-surface">{ex.en}</span>
                {getExampleTranslation(ex) && (
                  <span class="text-on-surface-variant/50 ml-2">— {getExampleTranslation(ex)}</span>
                )}
              </span>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        <!-- Abbreviations -->
        <div class="px-5 pb-3">
          <p class="text-on-surface-variant/50 text-xs">{getAbbrevNote(rule)}</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Native-language note -->
        {getRuleNote(rule.name) && (
          <div class="mx-5 mb-4 p-3 rounded-xl bg-primary/5 border border-primary/15 text-xs text-on-surface-variant/80 leading-relaxed">
            <span class="text-primary font-semibold">{copy.noteLabel} </span>{getRuleNote(rule.name)}
          </div>
        )}
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Common Mistakes -->
<section class="mb-12">
  <h2 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-6 flex items-center gap-2">
    <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-primary" style="font-size:22px">error</span>
    {copy.commonMistakesTitle}
  </h2>
  <div class="space-y-3">
    {[
      {
        wrong: 'I am agree with you.',
        right: 'I agree with you.',
        note: '"Agree" is a verb, not an adjective — no "am" needed.',
        noteEs: '"Agree" es un verbo común → lo maneja DO. No hay "ser o estar" en la oración.',
        noteFr: '"Agree" est un verbe courant : il est géré par DO. Il n’y a pas l’idée de "être" dans cette phrase.',
        noteDe: '"Agree" ist ein normales Verb und wird von DO gesteuert. In diesem Satz gibt es keine "sein"-Bedeutung.',
        notePt: '"Agree" é um verbo comum: ele é controlado por DO. Não existe ideia de "ser/estar" nessa frase.',
      },
      {
        wrong: "She don't know the answer.",
        right: "She doesn't know the answer.",
        note: 'Third-person singular (he/she/it) uses "doesn\'t" in the negative.',
        noteEs: "He/She/It usa DOES, no DO. Negativo: DOESN'T.",
        noteFr: 'He/She/It utilise DOES, pas DO. À la forme négative : DOESN’T.',
        noteDe: 'He/She/It nutzt DOES, nicht DO. In der Verneinung: DOESN’T.',
        notePt: 'He/She/It usa DOES, não DO. Na negativa: DOESN’T.',
      },
      {
        wrong: 'I have went to the market.',
        right: 'I have gone to the market.',
        note: 'Present perfect (HABER) requires the past participle, not the simple past.',
        noteEs: 'HAVE + participio pasado (gone, eaten, slept). "Went" es pasado simple, no participio.',
        noteFr: 'HAVE + participe passé (gone, eaten, slept). "Went" est le prétérit, pas le participe passé.',
        noteDe: 'HAVE + Partizip Perfekt (gone, eaten, slept). "Went" ist einfache Vergangenheit, nicht das Partizip.',
        notePt: 'HAVE + particípio passado (gone, eaten, slept). "Went" é passado simples, não particípio.',
      },
      {
        wrong: 'Yesterday I have seen him.',
        right: 'Yesterday I saw him.',
        note: '"Yesterday" signals a specific past time — use past simple (DID rule), not present perfect.',
        noteEs: '"Yesterday" indica tiempo pasado específico → usa DO/DID (pasado simple), no HAVE.',
        noteFr: '"Yesterday" indique un moment précis du passé : utilisez le prétérit avec DID, pas le present perfect.',
        noteDe: '"Yesterday" zeigt einen konkreten Zeitpunkt in der Vergangenheit: nutze Simple Past mit DID, nicht Present Perfect.',
        notePt: '"Yesterday" indica um tempo passado específico: use passado simples com DID, não present perfect.',
      },
      {
        wrong: 'He is more taller than her.',
        right: 'He is taller than her.',
        note: 'Never use "more" with -er comparatives.',
        noteEs: 'Con adjetivos cortos + "-er": solo usa el comparativo. "More" es para adjetivos largos.',
        noteFr: 'Avec les adjectifs courts en "-er", n’ajoutez pas "more". "More" sert aux adjectifs plus longs.',
        noteDe: 'Bei kurzen Adjektiven mit "-er" nutzt du kein "more". "More" ist für längere Adjektive.',
        notePt: 'Com adjetivos curtos + "-er", não use "more". "More" é para adjetivos mais longos.',
      },
    ].map((item) => (
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl bg-surface-container border border-outline-variant/15 text-sm">
        <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
          <span class="text-error font-bold shrink-0 mt-0.5">✗</span>
          <span class="text-on-surface-variant line-through">{item.wrong}</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-3 items-start mt-1">
          <span class="text-primary font-bold shrink-0 mt-0.5">✓</span>
          <span class="text-on-surface font-medium">{item.right}</span>
        </div>
        <p class="text-on-surface-variant/70 text-xs mt-2 ml-6">
          {getMistakeNote(item)}
        </p>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Articles -->
<section class="mb-12">
  <h2 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-6 flex items-center gap-2">
    <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-primary" style="font-size:22px">article</span>
    {copy.articlesTitle}
  </h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto">
    <table class="w-full text-sm text-left border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="border-b border-outline-variant/20">
          <th class="py-2 pr-6 text-on-surface-variant font-medium">{copy.articleHeaders[0]}</th>
          <th class="py-2 pr-6 text-on-surface-variant font-medium">{copy.articleHeaders[1]}</th>
          <th class="py-2 text-on-surface-variant font-medium">{copy.articleHeaders[2]}</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="text-on-surface-variant">
        <tr class="border-b border-outline-variant/10">
          <td class="py-2.5 pr-6 text-primary font-bold">a</td>
          <td class="py-2.5 pr-6">{copy.articleUses[0]}</td>
          <td class="py-2.5">I saw <em class="text-on-surface not-italic">a</em> cat.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-outline-variant/10">
          <td class="py-2.5 pr-6 text-primary font-bold">an</td>
          <td class="py-2.5 pr-6">{copy.articleUses[1]}</td>
          <td class="py-2.5">She ate <em class="text-on-surface not-italic">an</em> apple.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-outline-variant/10">
          <td class="py-2.5 pr-6 text-primary font-bold">the</td>
          <td class="py-2.5 pr-6">{copy.articleUses[2]}</td>
          <td class="py-2.5"><em class="text-on-surface not-italic">The</em> cat is on the roof.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-2.5 pr-6 text-on-surface-variant/60 italic">{copy.noneLabel}</td>
          <td class="py-2.5 pr-6">{copy.articleUses[3]}</td>
          <td class="py-2.5"><em class="text-on-surface not-italic">Dogs</em> are loyal animals.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  {currentLocale !== 'en' && copy.articleNote && (
    <p class="text-on-surface-variant/70 text-xs mt-3 p-3 rounded-xl bg-surface-container border border-outline-variant/10">
      <span class="text-primary font-semibold">{copy.noteLabel}</span> {copy.articleNote}
    </p>
  )}
</section>

<!-- Why it helps -->
<section class="p-6 rounded-2xl bg-primary/5 border border-primary/15">
  <h3 class="font-headline font-semibold text-primary mb-2 flex items-center gap-2">
    <span class="material-symbols-outlined" style="font-size:18px">record_voice_over</span>
    {copy.whyTitle}
  </h3>
  <p class="text-on-surface-variant leading-relaxed text-sm">
    {copy.whyBody}
  </p>
</section>
